GIT

Definition: Git is a distributed version control system (VCS) used to track changes in source code during software development.

Purpose: It allows multiple developers to work on the project simultaneously without overwriting each other's changes.

Key Features
    --> Tracks version history of files
    --> Supports branching and merging
    --> Works locally (offline capability)
    --> ensures code integrity through sha- checksums

Common git commands
    --> git init = initialize a repo
    --> git clone = copy an exisiting repo
    --> git add = stage changes
    --> git commit = save changes to local repo
    --> git push/pull = sync with remote repo


GITHUB

Definition: GitHub is a cloud based hosting service for Git repositories

Purpose: It provides a platform for collaboration code sharing and project management using git

Key Features
    --> Remote repo hosting
    --> Pull Requests for code reviews
    --> Issue tracking and project boards
    --> Integration with CI/CD tools


Git = Tool (for version control)

GitHub = Platform (for hosting git repos and collaboration)
